passages.text: 30+ delinquency rates for auto loan ABS have trended higher since the middle of 2021. We expect credit performance for most types of consumer debt, including auto debt, to deteriorate at a modest pace through most of this year with the potential for stability in metrics by year- end, but risks appear skewed to the downside.

Lower FICO buckets have weaker credit performance. Between October 2023 and early 2025, the prime and superprime cohorts had deteriorated at a faster pace, albeit from much lower absolute delinquency levels compared to nonprime and subprime (Exhibit 1 and Exhibit 2). The pace of deterioration has converged in recent months.

As measured by \(30+\) day delinquency (DG) rate, the 2022 and 2023 vintage (loan origination year) are the worst performing vintage among the 2018- 2023 vintage for all FICO cohorts. The 2024 vintage delinquency curves are tracking in line with (nonprime/subprime) or above (prime+) the 2023 vintage. With respect to cumulative gross defaults (CGD) by vintage, the 2023 vintage is relatively flat to lower than the 2022 vintage across FICO buckets with the subprime cohort seeing the most noticeable improvement.

All platforms are exhibiting higher defaults in the 2022 vintage relative to 2021. Looking at the 2022 and 2023 vintage, we find dispersion among platforms. Generally, lenders focused on prime borrowers are showing continued deterioration in the 2023 vintage compared to the 2022 vintage, while lenders focused on subprime borrowers are showing improvement. We think this can be attributed to uneven changes in underwriting standards over time, varied impact of macro factors, and likely seasonal changes in marketing/incentive financing for the captives.

Our asset- level database for auto ABS has the initial and ongoing data on individual loans or leases backing all SEC registered transactions issued since the beginning of 2017 (400+ loan transactions) in this report, we analyze trends in performance by borrower cohorts (e.g., FICO income, loan origination year). This analysis differs from our Retail auto loan and lease ABS performance report which tracks performance at the trust level.

Our asset level data shows subprime and low- income cohorts have the highest delinquency rates, but the pace of deterioration has converged among FICO buckets and is fastest for high income cohorts.

Delinquency rates for auto loan ABS have trended higher since the middle of 2021, moving away from historic lows reached during the pandemic. Our views on consumer credit performance remain cautious as elevated levels of policy uncertainty has increased the risk of a slowdown in economic activity. We expect modestly weaker performance with the possibility of stable performance closer to year- end.

We think potential weakness due to an economic downturn and higher unemployment (not the base case) could be partly offset by prior tightening in lending standards and relatively strong household balance sheets. Also, auto debt ranks high in payment priority (second after mortgage & rent payments, see payment priority).

We believe the pickup in inflation starting in early 2021 disproportionately affected lower FICO and lower income borrowers. In addition, loosening of underwriting standards from 4Q20 through 1Q22 likely contributed to weaker credit performance. While delinquencies continue to rise YoY for all FICO buckets and income cohorts, the pace of deterioration suggests that subprime and lower income cohorts cycled through the worst credits before higher FICO and higher income cohorts. Further, softer performance for higher FICO borrowers for the 2022- 2023 vintages could partly be attributed to FICO migration.

For June 2025, our asset level database for retail auto loan ABS1 shows lower FICO buckets have weaker credit performance. Between October 2023 and early 2025, the prime and superprime cohorts had deteriorated at faster pace, albeit from much lower absolute delinquency levels compared to nonprime and subprime (Exhibit 1 and Exhibit 2). The pace of deterioration has converged in recent months. The subprime cohort delinquency performance had stabilized from August to November 2024, but has increased YoY in December 2024 through June 2025.
Exhibit 1: 30+ days delinquencies by FICO bucket, 2019-2025 As expected, lower FICO buckets have weaker credit performance
Source: Transactions'SEC filings, BofA Global Research
Exhibit 2: YoY rate of change in 30+ day delinquencies by FICO bucket, 2019-2025
Source: Transactions'SEC filings, BofA Global Research '3 month average
The lower income tercile has the highest delinquency rate but the higher income tercile has the highest YoY rate of deterioration currently (Exhibit 3 and Exhibit 4).

The tercile calculation divides auto loan borrower incomes into three terciles (i.e., three groups, each representing one third of the data), separated by two income thresholds. The income thresholds are based on the borrower income distribution for all auto loans in a given month. The income thresholds between these terciles can move over time, reflecting any number of factors that impact income, including wage inflation.
Exhibit 3: 30+ day DQ by income tercile, 2019-2025 Highest income borrowers have the lowest DQ rate.
Source: Transactions'SEC filings, BofA Global Research
Exhibit 4: YoY rate of change in 30+ day DQ by income tercile (3-month average), 2019-2025
Source: Transactions'SEC filings, BofA Global Research

As measured by 30+ day delinquency rate, the 2022 and 2023 vintages (loan origination year) are the worst performing vintages among the 2018- 2023 vintages for all FICO cohorts (Exhibit 5, Exhibit 7, Exhibit 9, Exhibit 11). The 2023 vintage for nonprime loans is trending higher than the 2022 vintage while the 2023 vintage for superprime is trending lower than the 2022 vintage. The 2024 vintage delinquency curves are tracking in line with (nonprime/subprime) or above (prime+) the 2023 vintage. For this analysis, we exclude loans that were more than 12 months seasoned at the ABS transaction issuance date.
BofA GLOBAL RESEARCH

With respect to cumulative gross defaults (CGD) by vintage, the 2023 vintage is trending in line with the 2022 vintage across FICO buckets, except the subprime bucket is lower (Exhibit 6, Exhibit 8, Exhibit 10, Exhibit 12). The subprime cohort is seeing the most significant improvement for the 2023 vintage versus 2022 vintage, while prime and superprime cohorts are seeing fairly comparable performance. Lenders likely tightened underwriting standards earlier for subprime borrowers since these borrowers exhibited the first signs of post pandemic stress. We believe the pickup in inflation starting in 2021 disproportionately affected lower FICO and lower income borrowers.

The 60- to- 90+ days roll rates and 90+ day delinquency- to- default roll rates are below pre- pandemic levels across all FICO cohorts. Meanwhile the 30- to- 60 days roll rates are above pre- pandemic levels for all cohorts. This suggests borrowers are more likely to enter early- stage delinquency but are now more likely to cure compared to 2019 and explains the elevated delinquency rates for the 2023 vintage but lower defaults (see Exhibit 13 to Exhibit 16).
Subprime and nonprime FICO cohorts are significantly more likely to transition into early-stage delinquency.
Source: Transactions'SEC filings, BofA Global Research

Exhibit 21 to Exhibit 28 show annual (2020- 2023), half (2024) loan vintage cumulative gross loss performance for eight auto loan ABS platforms. All platforms are exhibiting higher defaults in the 2022 vintage relative to 2021. We note that the ABS may not be representative of the lenders' overall managed portfolios.

Looking at the 2022 and 2023 vintages, we find dispersion among platforms in performance trends. Generally, lenders focused on prime borrowers are showing continued deterioration in the 2023 vintage compared to the 2022 vintage, while lenders focused on subprime borrowers are showing improvement. We think this can be attributed to uneven changes in underwriting standards over time, varied impacts of macro factors, and likely seasonal changes in marketing/incentive financing for the captives. Platforms targeting subprime borrowers appear to have tightened lending standards earlier than those platforms that target prime borrowers.
2022 vintage has the highest cumulative defaults. The 2023 and 1H24 is trending in line with the 2022 vintage.
